    "markdown": "## MSK Guided Injection 1 Ultrasound Scan Overview\n\n- \\*\\*What it does:\\*\\* Combines high-resolution imaging with a single, accurate medication injection\n- \\*\\*Duration:\\*\\* Complete visit—including scan, injection, and recovery—takes ≤30 minutes\n- \\*\\*Goal:\\*\\* Pinpoint the exact source of pain and deliver medicine where it’s needed most\n## What Is an MSK Guided Injection 1 Ultrasound Scan?\n### Real-time ultrasound guidance explained\nA small probe glides over your skin, sending painless sound waves into the joint or tendon. The live picture appears on a monitor, letting the physician watch the needle travel to the precise trouble spot.\n### Diagnostic vs therapeutic injection\n- \\*\\*Diagnostic:\\*\\* A tiny amount of anesthetic confirms the pain source.\n- \\*\\*Therapeutic:\\*\\* Steroids, hyaluronic acid, PRP, or Botox are injected for long-term relief.\n## Types of MSK Guided Injections\n- \\*\\*Corticosteroid\\*\\* – fast anti-inflammatory\n- \\*\\*Hyaluronic acid\\*\\* – joint lubrication for osteoarthritis\n- \\*\\*Platelet-rich plasma (PRP)\\*\\* – healing boost for tendons\n- \\*\\*Botulinum toxin (Botox)\\*\\* – muscle spasticity relief\n\n## When and Who Needs This Scan?\n\nLook for these signs:\n- Joint pain lasting >6 weeks\n- Tendonitis or bursitis flare-ups\n- Sports injuries (tennis elbow, runner’s knee)\n- Chronic inflammatory conditions like rheumatoid arthritis\n\n## Risks & Limitations\n\n- Common but mild: tiny bruise, brief swelling\n- Rare: infection (1 in 10,000)\n- Limitations: very deep joints or high BMI may need MRI guidance instead\n\n## Parameters Assessed During the Scan\n\n- Joint effusion volume (excess fluid)\n- Tendon integrity & sheath thickness\n- Needle placement accuracy in real time\n\n## Reasons for Taking the Test\n\n- Confirm the exact pain generator\n- Deliver medication directly, avoiding pill side-effects\n- Reduce or eliminate the need for surgery\n\n## Benefits of Ultrasound-Guided Precision\n\n- \\*\\*Higher accuracy:\\*\\* up to 96 % vs 60 % for blind injections\n- \\*\\*Radiation-free:\\*\\* safe for repeated use\n- \\*\\*Faster recovery:\\*\\* shorter procedure, less tissue trauma\n\n## Illnesses Diagnosed & Treated\n\n- Rotator-cuff tendinopathy\n- Plantar fasciitis\n- Carpal tunnel syndrome\n- Frozen shoulder\n- Golfer’s or tennis elbow\n\n## Preparing for Your Appointment\n\n- \\*\\*Bring:\\*\\* List of current medications and any recent imaging reports\n- \\*\\*Do NOT fast\\*\\*—eat and drink normally\n- \\*\\*Wear:\\*\\* Loose clothing that exposes the target joint or limb\n## Pre-requisites\n- Disclose blood-thinning meds (aspirin, warfarin)\n- Notify staff of allergies to local anesthetics or latex\n- Arrange a short ride if you feel anxious about needles\n## Best Time & Eligibility\n- \\*\\*When:\\*\\* Any time of day; avoid during active skin infection\n- \\*\\*Who:\\*\\* Adults and teens ≥15 kg; pregnancy cases handled individually\n## Step-by-Step Procedure\n1. \\*\\*Consent\\*\\* – explanation and signature\n2. \\*\\*Skin prep\\*\\* – sterile wipe and mark\n3. \\*\\*Ultrasound scan\\*\\* – locate problem area\n4. \\*\\*Needle insertion\\*\\* – watch live on screen\n5. \\*\\*Injection\\*\\* – medication delivered\n6. \\*\\*Monitoring\\*\\* – 10 minutes observation before discharge\n## Caution Before Taking the Test\nTell the team if you are: pregnant, breastfeeding, allergic to lidocaine, or on strong blood thinners."
  },
